Jun 15 2008 	Chelsea Inn a great find!	We stayed in the Chelsea Motor Inn for 4 nights while we visited San Francisco in May 2008. It was possibly the cleanest hotel we have ever been in. It’s a little weird to get to – you must pull into the “car lobby” in your car, and then walk into the small office to check in. All of the staff were very friendly and answered our questions with a smile. Once we got our room keys, we pulled into the underground parking garage and just left our car there for the duration. You need your room key to get into the elevator, so it felt like coming and going from our own apartment. The smoke free property and free parking was a great plus for us. We booked directly with the hotel by phone. For the price of $101/night, we felt like we got a good bargain. Our room itself on the second floor was a decent size, with a very comfortable king bed, plenty of pillows, a desk, and a bay window with chair and footstool. The bathroom had a nice large counter, and the amenities were replenished as needed. The wireless internet worked nicely. The small coffee pot came in handy every morning, and the coffee was actually very good. There was plenty of storage and closet space, but we were glad we brought some extra hangers with us. While the building is certainly not new, the cleanliness and understated elegance really pleased us. Our room faced a side street, so the traffic noise didn’t bother us. We heard a few drunken parties Saturday and Sunday nights, though. Unknown to us, this was the weekend of the annual Bay to Breakers Run, so I think the noise stemmed from that, as we didn’t hear anything Monday or Tuesday nights. This hotel is one block from the main #30 bus route. I highly recommend buying a 3-day unlimited transit pass. This is available at a few places, including the cable car turn-around at Fisherman’s wharf. This got us on all buses, trolleys and cable cars as much as we wanted. We got all over the city with this. Check out the muni.com website for travel distances and estimated times. While we did walk to fisherman’s wharf once, it’s really quite a distance, considering you’ll be walking around there, also. Take the bus – it’s an experience, if nothing else! There’s a laundromat just a couple of blocks up Lombard and around the corner, which we took advantage of while we were there.There’s a great little pizza joint just down Lombard street from the Chelsea, but I can’t remember the name of it. It’s on the same side of the street and only about a block away, past the KFC. It looks like a hole in the wall, but the pizza was delicious!	
